    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-11-24T16:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-11-24T16:00:00-05:00" n="567"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d567">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 103.97/51</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Food Administration Representative at London</hi>
                        (<persName corresp="#p_SLP1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Sheldon</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the Food Administrator</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="#p_HHC1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Hoover</hi>
                    </persName>)<note n="2" xml:id="d567fn2">Transmitted by the Ambassador in Great
                        Britain through the Secretary of State (No. 7808).</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-11-24T21:00:00+00:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">November 24, 1917, 9 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received November 25, 4.30 a.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>No. 81. <persName corresp="#p_RLD1">Rhondda</persName> communicates: <quote
                        rend="blockquote">
                        <p>I am seriously alarmed by your cable and Doctor <persName
                                corresp="#p_TAE1">Taylor</persName>’s confidential statement that
                            the total exportable wheat surplus from United States and Canada will
                            not exceed 133,000,000 bushels. Unless Allies can rely on North American
                            exports considerably in excess <pb facs="0736" n="662" xml:id="pg_662"/>
                            of these figures and upon a larger amount of grain than is now being
                            allocated we shall be confronted with a situation of extreme gravity. I
                            am exerting every effort to reduce the estimated Allied requirements to
                            the bare minimum consistent with military efficiency but when all
                            possible reductions and all probable imports from other sources are
                            allowed for there remains on the basis of your figures a serious
                            deficiency. In view of this situation I earnestly trust that either by
                            dilution or other measures you will find a way to increase this year’s
                            exportable surplus.</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SLP1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Sheldon</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
